# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: url-pattern-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] Since September 2025, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] The **`URLPattern`** interface of the URL Pattern API matches URLs or parts of URLs against a pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] The pattern can contain capturing groups that extract parts of the matched URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] More information about the syntax of patterns can be found on the API overview page: URL Pattern API.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] Returns a new `URLPattern` object based on the given pattern and base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *hash* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A boolean indicating whether or not any of the `URLPattern` components contain regular expression capturing groups.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *hostname* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *password* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *pathname* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *port* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *protocol* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *search* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] A string containing a pattern to match the *username* part of a URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] Returns an object with the matched parts of the URL or `null` if the URL does not match.
[src:url-pattern-api/api-urlpattern] Returns `true` if the URL matches the given pattern, `false` otherwise.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:url-pattern-api/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The **URL Pattern API** defines a syntax that is used to create URL pattern matchers.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] These patterns can be matched against URLs or individual URL components.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Patterns are specified using the `URLPattern` interface.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The pattern syntax is based on the syntax from the path-to-regexp library.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] You can find details about the syntax in the pattern syntax section below.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Represents a pattern that can match URLs or parts of URLs.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The syntax for patterns is based on the path-to-regexp JavaScript library.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This syntax is similar to the one used in Ruby on Rails, or JavaScript frameworks like Express or Next.js.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Each pattern can contain a combination of fixed text and groups.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The fixed text is a sequence of characters that is matched exactly.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Groups match an arbitrary string based on matching rules.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Each URL part has its own default rules that are explained below, but they can be overwritten.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] By default, a group matching the `pathname` part of the URL will match all characters but the forward slash (`/`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In the `hostname` part, the group will match all characters except the dot (`.`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In all other parts, the group will match all characters.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The segment wildcard is non-greedy, meaning that it will match the shortest possible string.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Instead of using the default match rules for a group, you can specify a regex for each group by specifying it in parentheses.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This regex defines the matching rules for the group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] You can also use regex when constructing a `URLPattern` with the object syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `pathname` URL-part always starts with `/`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] If you omit the `/` in your regular expression the match will fail.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The start of line anchor (`^`) and end-of line anchor (`$`) are used to anchor patterns to the start and end of the test string, respectively.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] While these can be specified for the start and end of a URL-part they are redundant.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This is because all URL-parts are implicitly preceded by the `^` anchor, and followed by the `$` anchor.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following code demonstrates that it doesn't matter whether or not `^` is specified.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The example uses a pattern in the `protocol` URL-part, but the other parts of the URL behave the same.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The code below demonstrates that it doesn't matter whether or not `$` is specified.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Lookahead and lookbehind asserts allow you to specify that text ahead or behind the current parsing position matches a particular pattern, without that match being captured, or the characters being consumed.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Be careful when using lookahead and lookbehind assertions with `URLPattern`, as there is some behavior you may find unintuitive.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For example, you would expect the following lookahead assertion to match a `pathname` of `/ab`, but this is not what happens.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `URLPattern` engine matches the test string against the `pathname` pattern, first finding the match for `/a` and then asserts that the next character in the test URL is `b` — but not consuming it.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The engine continues matching the test URL at the unconsumed character `b`, but there is nothing left in the pattern to match it against, which causes the match to fail.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For the match to work the pattern has to consume all the characters in the test string.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The next example shows a negative lookahead match for `/a` which is not followed by `b`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Note that the assertion is followed by `.*` to consume the character matched by the assertion.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows a positive lookbehind match that matches on a pathname like `/ba`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The pattern matches `/`, then `.` to consume the next character, followed by the assertion that the previous character was a `b`, and then an `a`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This example shows a negative lookbehind match that matches on a pathname like `/<not b>a`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The pattern matches `/`, then `.` to consume the next character (`x`), followed by the assertion that the previous character was not `b`, and then an `a`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Named groups are specified by prefixing the group name with a colon (`:`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Regex groups that are not prefixed by a colon and a name are unnamed.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Unnamed groups are numerically indexed in the match result based on their order in the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] These are specified after the group name (or after the regex if there is one).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] There are three modifiers: `?` to make the group optional, `+` to make the group repeat one or more times, and `*` to make the group repeat zero or more times.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Patterns can also contain group delimiters.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] These are pieces of a pattern that are surrounded by curly braces (`{}`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] These group delimiters are not captured in the match result like capturing groups, but can still have modifiers applied to them, just like groups.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] If group delimiters are not modified by a modifier, they are treated as if the items in them were just part of the parent pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Group delimiters may not contain other group delimiters, but may contain any other pattern items (capturing groups, regex, wildcard, or fixed text).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In patterns that match against the `pathname` part of a URL, groups get an automatic slash (`/`) prefix added if the group definition is preceded by a slash (`/`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This is useful for groups with modifiers, as it allows for repeating groups to work as expected.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] If you do not want automatic prefixing, you can disable it by surrounding the group with group delimiters (`{}`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Group delimiters do not have automatic prefixing behavior.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The wildcard token (`*`) is a shorthand for an unnamed capturing group that matches all characters zero or more times.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] You can place this anywhere in the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The wildcard is greedy, meaning that it will match the longest possible string.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Trailing slashes in a pathname are not automatically matched.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] If you want to match both then you need to use a match pattern that allows either.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The easiest approach is to use a group delimiter that contains a forward slash, followed by the optional modifier.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This will match the pattern with or without a terminating forward slash.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] When a pattern is parsed it is automatically normalized to a canonical form.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For example, Unicode characters are percent-encoded in the pathname property, punycode encoding is used in the hostname, default port numbers are elided, paths like `/foo/./bar/` are collapsed to `/foo/bar`, etc.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In addition, there are some pattern representations that parse to the same underlying meaning, like `foo` and `{foo}`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Such cases are normalized to the simplest form.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In this case `{foo}` is normalized to `foo`, for example.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] If a base URL is defined then URL-parts *may* be inherited from the base URL and used to set parts of the pattern or test URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] URL resolution is much the same as you would expect when resolving a `URL` that is specified with a base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `username` and `password` are never inherited from the base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Only URL parts that are "more specific" than the most-specific part defined in the input will be inherited from the base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] What this means, for example, is that if the `protocol` is specified in the input URL, then nothing is more specific, so nothing will be inherited from the base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] However if the `pathname` part is specified in the input, the `protocol`, `hostname` and `port` may be inherited from the base URL, but the `search` and `hash` will not.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Note that URL components that are not specified in the string/input object or inherited from the base URL will default to the wildcard value (`"*"`) for a `URLPattern` and to the empty string (`""`) for a test URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The URL Pattern API treats many parts of the URL as case-sensitive by default when matching.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In contrast, many client-side JavaScript frameworks use case-insensitive URL matching.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] An `ignoreCase` option is available on the `URLPattern()` constructor to enable case-insensitive matching if desired.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how a `URLPattern` filters a specific URL component.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] When the `URLPattern()` constructor is called with a structured object of component patterns any missing components default to the `*` wildcard value.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how to construct a `URLPattern` from a full URL string with embedded patterns.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For example, a `:` can be both the URL protocol suffix, like `https:`, and the beginning of a named pattern group, like `:foo`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] It "just works" if there is no ambiguity between whether a character is part of the URL syntax or part of the pattern syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how a `URLPattern` constructed from an ambiguous string will favor treating characters as part of the pattern syntax.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In this case the `:` character could be the protocol component suffix or it could be the prefix for a named group in the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The constructor chooses to treat this as part of the pattern and therefore determines this is a relative pathname pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Since there is no base URL the relative pathname cannot be resolved and it throws an error.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how an ambiguous constructor string character can be escaped to be treated as a URL separator instead of a pattern character.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how `test()` and `exec()` can use base URLs.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how base URLs can also be used to construct the `URLPattern`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The base URL is treated strictly as a URL and cannot contain any pattern syntax itself.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The pattern only inherits URL parts from the base URL that are less specific than those in the other properties.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In this case the `pathname` is specified so the protocol and host can be inherited, but not the search, hash, username, or password.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The properties that are not inherited default to the wildcard string (`"*"`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The exception is the port, which is set to the empty string because the *hostname* is inherited from the base URL (which has an implied "default port" value).
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how input values that match pattern groups can later be accessed from the `exec()` result object.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `input` property is the string that is matched by the pattern: in this case it's `cdn.example.com`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `groups` property contains captured groups, indexed by number for unnamed groups, and name for named groups.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In this case, there is only one unnamed group for the wildcard property, with the value `cdn`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how groups can be given custom names which can be used to access the matched value in the result object.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The match patterns in the pattern are indicated by the `:` symbol followed by a name.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The same names then appear as keys in the `groups` property, with the matching values being the matched part of the test URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The `input` property contains the whole part of the URL that matched the `pathname` pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how a matching group can use a regular expression to match either `/foo` or `/bar` in a test URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The group is unnamed, so will be referenced by an index number in the result.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how to use a custom regular expression with a named group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The group is named `type`, and matches a path which is either `/foo` or `/bar`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how to make a matching group optional by placing a `?` modifier after it.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For the pathname component this also causes any preceding `/` character to be treated as an optional prefix to the group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] This may not seem to make sense since they already match the empty string, but it also makes the prefix `/` optional in a pathname pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how a matching group can be made repeated by placing a `+` modifier after it.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] In the `pathname` component this also treats the `/` prefix as special, so that it is effectively the start of the repeating group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Note that `/product` does not match because it is not followed by `/` and at least one character.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how to make a matching group that is both optional and repeated.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Do this by placing a `*` modifier after the group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Again, the pathname component treats the `/` prefix as special.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] It both becomes optional and is also repeated with the group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] Note that unlike the previous example, `/product` matches because the repeating segments, including `/` are optional.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] However there must be at least one character to capture after a forward slash to match the repeating group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how curly braces (a group delimiter) can be with a named group to denote a custom prefix and/or suffix to be operated on by a subsequent `?`, `*`, or `+` modifier.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] For example, `{:subdomain.}*` matches against any subdomain of `example.com` and the domain itself.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The match is assigned to the named group "subdomain".
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how curly braces can be used to denote fixed text values as optional or repeated without using a matching group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The pattern below matches either `/product` or `/product/` but because group delimiter are non-capturing by default, the result is not found in a corresponding match group.
[src:url-pattern-api/url-pattern-api] The following example shows how many features can be combined across multiple URL components.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A **uniform resource locator** (**URL**), colloquially known as a **web address**, is a reference to a resource on the World Wide Web.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A URL specifies the location of a resource on a computer network and a mechanism for retrieving it.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A URL is a specific type of Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), although many people use the two terms interchangeably.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A URL is most commonly used to reference a web page (HTTP/HTTPS) but is also used for file transfer (FTP), email (mailto), database access (JDBC), and many other applications.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Most web browsers display the URL of a web page above the page in an address bar.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] As an example of a web page URL, `https://www.example.com/index.html` indicates protocol `https`, hostname `www.example.com`, and file name `index.html`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The Uniform Resource Locator was defined in RFC 1738 in 1994 by Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, and the URI working group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), as an outcome of collaboration started at the IETF Living Documents birds of a feather session in 1992.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The format combines the pre-existing system of domain names (created in 1985) with file path syntax, where slashes are used to separate directory and filenames.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Conventions already existed where server names could be prefixed to complete file paths, preceded by a double slash (`//`).
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Berners-Lee later expressed regret at the use of dots to separate the parts of the domain name within URIs, wishing he had used slashes throughout, and also said that, given the colon following the first component of a URI, the two slashes before the domain name were unnecessary.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Early WorldWideWeb collaborators, including Berners-Lee, originally proposed the use of UDIs: Universal Document Identifiers.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] An early (1993) draft of the HTML Specification referred to "Universal" Resource Locators.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] This was dropped some time between June 1994 and October 1994.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] In his book *Weaving the Web*, Berners-Lee emphasizes his preference for the original inclusion of "universal" in the expansion rather than the word "uniform", to which it was later changed, and he gives a brief account of the contention that led to the change.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Every HTTP URL conforms to the syntax of a generic URI.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A component is *undefined* if it has an associated delimiter and the delimiter does not appear in the URI; the scheme and path components are always defined.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A component is *empty* if it has no characters; the scheme component is always non-empty.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] A web browser will usually dereference a URL by performing an HTTP request to the specified host, by default on port number 80.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] URLs using the `https` scheme require that requests and responses be made over a secure connection to the website.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Internet users are distributed throughout the world using a wide variety of languages and alphabets, and expect to be able to create URLs in their own local alphabets.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] An Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) is a form of URL that includes Unicode characters.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The parts of the URL requiring special treatment for different alphabets are the domain name and path.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The domain name in the IRI is known as an Internationalized Domain Name (IDN).
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Web and Internet software automatically convert the domain name into punycode usable by the Domain Name System; for example, the Chinese URL `http://例子.卷筒纸` becomes `http://xn--fsqu00a.xn--3lr804guic/`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The `xn--` indicates that the character was not originally ASCII.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The URL path name can also be specified by the user in the local writing system.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] If not already encoded, it is converted to UTF-8, and any characters not part of the basic URL character set are escaped as hexadecimal using percent-encoding; for example, the Japanese URL `http://example.com/引き割り.html` becomes `http://example.com/%E5%BC%95%E3%81%8D%E5%89%B2%E3%82%8A.html`.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] The target computer decodes the address and displays the page.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] Protocol-relative links (PRL), also known as protocol-relative URLs (PRURL), are URLs that have no protocol specified.
[src:url-pattern-api/url] For example, `//example.com` will use the protocol of the current page, typically HTTP or HTTPS.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The **`exec()`** method of the `URLPattern` interface takes a URL or object of URL parts, and returns either an object containing the results of matching the URL to the pattern, or `null` if the URL does not match the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] An object providing the individual URL parts.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The object members can be any of `protocol`, `username`, `password`, `hostname`, `port`, `pathname`, `search`, `hash`, or `baseURL`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] A string defining an absolute or relative URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] If a relative URL, then `baseURL` must also be provided and together they must resolve to an absolute URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] If the input cannot be parsed, or a relative URL without a base URL is provided, the method will return `false`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] A string representing the base URL to use in cases where `url` is a relative URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] If not specified, it defaults to `undefined`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] If provided but the base URL cannot be parsed, the method will return `false`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] URL parts that are not specified in the `url`/`input` may be inherited from a base URL in some circumstances.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Omitted parts are treated as empty strings.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] An `Object` that defines the matching elements and groups, or `null` if the passed inputs do not match the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] An array containing the inputs passed to the `exec()` function.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] This will either contain a passed `input` object, an absolute `url` string, or a relative `url` and a `baseURL`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The part of the input corresponding to the current URL-part property (which must have matched the pattern).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] An object with properties for each match group in the URL part (if any), and the corresponding matched values in the inputs.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The group properties are numbered from 0 for unnamed match groups (such as the wildcard).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] For named match groups, the property name is the group name.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Indicates that a `baseURL` is provided when an `input` object is passed (it should only be passed with the `url` string).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The method is called on a `URLPattern`, specifying an input url as a string with an optional base URL, or as object with properties for each URL-part.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The method returns an object containing the results of matching the URL to the pattern, or `null` if the URL does not match the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] It also returns `null` if a relative `url` is passed but `baseURL` is not specified (an absolute test URL cannot be resolved).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Note that when passing an `input` object, `input.baseURL` is always optional.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] URL-parts that are more specific than the least-specific part defined in the `url` can be inherited from `baseURL` (or from `input.baseURL` for `input`).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Intuitively this means that if the `pathname` part is specified in the input, the parts to its left in a URL may be inherited from the base URL (`protocol`, `hostname` and `port`), while the parts to its right may not (`search` and `hash`).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The `username` and `password` are never inherited from a base URL.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] For more information see Inheritance from a BaseURL in the API overview.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] The examples shows how to use the `exec()` method to match a URL against a pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] First we define the pattern to use for matching URLs.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] This pattern matches against URLs that have either `http` or `https` protocol, are subdomains of `.example.com` and have a path that is `/books/` followed by any value.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Next we test the URL string `"https://store.example.com/books/123"` against this pattern, and then separately log the objects for each property.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Note that the `input` shows the input in the URL that matches the pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] In many cases this is the empty string (`""`) because the input URL does not specify the particular URL part (this matches the pattern because by default it uses a wildcard match for unspecified URL parts).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] Note also how the `pathname` input `"/books/123"` matches to the pattern `/books/:id`, and `groups` includes a named property `id` that contains the matched value in the input.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-exec] This example uses the same pattern as before to match against a number of relative URLs and their corresponding base URLs.
