[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The **`test()`** method of the `URLPattern` interface takes a URL string or object of URL parts, and returns a boolean indicating if the given input matches the current pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The method returns `true` if all components of the test URL/input match all components of the pattern, and `false` if any component don't match.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The method also returns `false` if a relative `url` is passed but `baseURL` is not specified (an absolute test URL cannot be resolved).
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The examples shows how to use the `test()` method to match a URL against a pattern.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] In each case the result of the `test()` is printed to the console.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] Next we match against two absolute URL strings.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The first matches but the second doesn't, because the test URL is not a subdomain of `example.com`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] This example uses the same pattern as before to test against a number of relative URLs.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] Next we match against some relative URLs.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] The case matches as the resolved URL is `https://store.example.com/books/123`, while the second does note because the resolved URL is not a subdomain of `example.com`.
[src:url-pattern-api/urlpattern-test] This test does not match because the provided URL is relative and no baseURL is provided.
